a little bit about your role and something you like to do outside of work, too.

00:01:57.680 --> 00:01:58.680
Sure.

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:00.440
So I'm Matt Fraser.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:05.559
I actually started in data science in 2008, right after the financial crisis.

00:02:05.559 --> 00:02:08.000
Prior to that, I was more of an insurance guy.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.360
I actually have a background in philosophy, specifically metaphysics.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:20.119
And so I'm sort of a Karl Popperian at heart, if anybody knows who Karl Popper is, who was

00:02:20.119 --> 00:02:21.559
the first empirical skeptic.

00:02:21.559 --> 00:02:29.080
And so I sort of transitioned my empirical skepticism over into data science and started

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:30.520
to learn it in 2008.

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:35.520
Before that, I carried a number of executive positions at different insurance companies

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:36.839
in the underwriting space.

00:02:36.839 --> 00:02:44.839
At that point in time, right, from let's say 1998 through 2008, I did not know of an

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:49.679
insurance company that was actually doing any predictive modeling at all.

00:02:49.679 --> 00:02:56.080
And it is still the case that really the national carriers are using AI, they're using data

00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:58.039
science, they're using predictive modeling.

00:02:58.039 --> 00:03:02.360
But most of the smaller mutuals, right, the ones that are only in a couple of states,

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:07.600
are really using other predictive modeling software as a service companies to do all

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:08.919
of their predictive modeling.

00:03:08.919 --> 00:03:16.720
So data science was a sort of an obvious transition after I made it, but I had no idea what the

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:19.039
heck it was before I got into it.

00:03:19.039 --> 00:03:20.360
I was just a philosophy guy.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:21.440
I was a language guy.

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:22.440
I love language.

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:25.800
And I love understanding what is knowable and what isn't knowable, right.

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:30.360
But I didn't really realize that you could translate that into mathematics until I got

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:33.279
into a company called Valen Technologies.

00:03:33.279 --> 00:03:39.880
So I sort of got out of the insurance industry and went into a company that was adjacent

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:45.360
to the insurance industry, actually selling to insurance companies, predictive analytic

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:47.880
and data science solutions, right.

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:51.639
But before that, I was pretty good on the actuarial side.

00:03:51.639 --> 00:03:56.639
I'm not a classically trained actuary at heart, but I was the director of pricing at a number

00:03:56.639 --> 00:04:01.839
of different insurance companies as I sort of progressed through my career.

00:04:01.839 --> 00:04:04.800
And so I got pretty good at using Excel, okay.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:06.839
I got pretty good at grinding through data.

00:04:06.839 --> 00:04:13.240
I get pretty good at philosophically understanding data and understanding, you know, what it

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:16.920
meant if certain data had low integrity versus high integrity and things like that.

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:21.000
So I was really good at data wrangling, but I didn't have any idea what a GLM was.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:24.839
And don't ask me to write any formulas down because, you know, I let you guys, I let the

00:04:24.839 --> 00:04:27.760
data scientists do that, right.

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:32.040
But I'm pretty good at picking models apart because of my empirical skepticism that I

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:36.359
learned at a very early sort of age through college and high school.

00:04:36.359 --> 00:04:37.799
My dad was a physician.

00:04:37.799 --> 00:04:40.920
He always used to kind of hammer me on, hey, are you sure you know that?

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:42.920
Do you know that or do you think you know that, right?

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:44.320
Do you believe you know that?

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:47.000
Because beliefs can be wrong.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.640
And so when I was at Valen, I was able to get trained by a former chief modeling officer

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:54.119
at Capital One.

00:04:54.119 --> 00:04:59.480
Capital One Technologies, one of the major investors was Nigel Morris, who was one of

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:01.359
the co-founders of Capital One.

00:05:01.359 --> 00:05:07.480
And Capital One was sort of one of the first banks that got into machine learning, got

00:05:07.480 --> 00:05:11.119
into predictive modeling on the credit card side.

00:05:11.119 --> 00:05:13.880
And so they had a very robust understanding.

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:16.959
They were one of the early adopters, let's say, in the banking space and the fintech

00:05:16.959 --> 00:05:21.959
space of actually using predictive models in order to create a competitive advantage

00:05:21.959 --> 00:05:25.279
or arbitrage opportunity within the credit card space.

00:05:25.279 --> 00:05:30.600
And so we were able to really capitalize on that connection with Capital One.

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:34.920
We were able to take some really smart people from Capital One, bring them into Valen.

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:41.880
And I really learned on the job from one of the former chief modeling officers on the

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:47.559
commercial auto and auto finance side from Capital One.

00:05:47.559 --> 00:05:51.399
And the second I got into it, I absolutely loved it.

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:53.440
I mean, Valen was my favorite job.

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:56.200
The second I got into data science, I was like, oh, God, this is what I've been missing

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:57.200
my whole life.

00:05:57.200 --> 00:05:58.200
Right.

00:05:58.200 --> 00:05:59.200
Like, I love the language.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:02.920
But to be able to blend the language and the math together, the language and the data together

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:09.679
and actually produce something that gives another company a moat or a competitive advantage

00:06:09.679 --> 00:06:12.279
in a marketplace, man, that's really cool.

00:06:12.279 --> 00:06:18.040
Like I can actually take things from the philosophy side where all you're really doing is creating

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:22.600
more questions for yourself and actually translating that into real, durable value

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:26.839
in the world, like something that's tangible, that can be seen through dollars and cents.

00:06:26.839 --> 00:06:31.000
I was super duper excited, you know, I got really excited about that.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.399
And then I translated that into Pi Insurance.

00:06:34.399 --> 00:06:39.359
I was one of the what I would call the silent co-founder at Pi.

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:45.640
We took all of the learnings that we were able to extract from Valen Technologies, working

00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:49.839
with about 56 different insurance companies in the property and casualty space.

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:54.200
And we translated that into building durable models that created a competitive advantage

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:57.440
and an arbitrage opportunity for Pi Insurance.

00:06:57.440 --> 00:07:03.119
Pi started in, oh, gosh, I want to say it was 2018 now.

00:07:03.119 --> 00:07:06.640
So we're now writing about 300 million.

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:10.559
We're on the path to about 350, maybe 400 million this year.

00:07:10.559 --> 00:07:18.480
And I believe we're the fastest growing and quickest, most capitalized in insure tech

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:20.399
that has ever existed.

00:07:20.399 --> 00:07:24.959
So somehow I was able to take that philosophy degree, translate it into data science, create

00:07:24.959 --> 00:07:30.040
a competitive advantage, and raise a whole bunch of money and create a company that now

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:31.040
employs.

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:33.959
Unfortunately, we just went through what we call a reduction force.

00:07:33.959 --> 00:07:39.320
But we had about 460 employees, we now have about 400 employees now.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:42.320
And I think that's the end of the cutting so far.

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:46.760
But I've been very pleased with what I've been able to do and what I've been able to

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:48.480
learn in data science.

00:07:48.480 --> 00:07:53.600
And I'm just looking forward to a lot more learning opportunities as we move forward.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:55.480
You asked, what do I like to do?

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:56.480
Yeah.

00:07:56.480 --> 00:08:01.239
Skiing, fly fishing, hiking, I like to be outside.

00:08:01.239 --> 00:08:06.839
So as long as it's outside and it's sort of a more of a single sport, I really like that

00:08:06.839 --> 00:08:07.839
kind of a thing.

00:08:07.839 --> 00:08:09.359
I'm not a big team sports guy.

00:08:09.359 --> 00:08:13.279
It's not that I'm not big on teams, because I'm huge on teams, I just don't play a lot

00:08:13.279 --> 00:08:14.279
of team sports.

00:08:14.279 --> 00:08:18.880
I play tennis and things like that, that are more double or single kind of thing.

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:24.880
Well, where are you outside right now in your background, your virtual background?

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:27.200
This is Wadi Rum.

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:30.119
So this is right near Petra in Jordan.

00:08:30.119 --> 00:08:35.880
And I try to keep it fresh with all my backgrounds, so I have goofy backgrounds like Animal House

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:38.200
in Casablanca and other things like that.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:40.280
This one just happened to be up on my Zoom today.

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:43.559
Well, thank you so much for joining us today, Matt.

00:08:43.559 --> 00:08:48.640
I feel like I can feel the energy from you and excitement coming through the computer.

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:52.960
So thank you for bringing the energy here today.

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:58.520
Something I really wanted to ask you about initially, because it's something that comes

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:01.619
up quite a bit in the data science Hangouts.

00:09:01.619 --> 00:09:06.140
So I know you wrote your bio for the Hangout with ChatGBT.

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:09.940
So I feel like this is a good place to start off.

00:09:09.940 --> 00:09:16.700
But I'd love to hear your thoughts on ChatGBT, but also AI in general, and how you think

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:19.419
it may impact the insurance industry.

00:09:19.419 --> 00:09:20.419
Okay.

00:09:20.419 --> 00:09:26.219
I'll start with in general, and then we'll go into insurance.

00:09:26.219 --> 00:09:31.460
There's a lot of people on both sides of one particular argument, and that is whether ChatGBT

00:09:32.299 --> 00:09:35.460
has the latest sort of tangible instantiation of AI, right?

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:36.780
Is AI going to take over the world?

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:41.940
Are we going to live in a terminator universe where AI eventually is significantly smarter

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:45.179
than us and somehow grows in tension?

00:09:45.179 --> 00:09:50.020
I'm in the camp that I think that artificial intelligence and large language models and

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:54.260
the like are going to be a benefit to society.

00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:56.340
They are not going to be a detractor to society.

00:09:56.340 --> 00:09:57.700
Now, do we have to be careful?

00:09:57.700 --> 00:09:59.020
Of course, right?

00:09:59.059 --> 00:10:04.580
Human beings are never at a space morally where we are technologically.

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:11.820
And so the technology is going to force us to re-evaluate or trans-evaluate our scale

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:12.940
of values, right?

00:10:12.940 --> 00:10:16.940
We're going to have to understand what can be done, and we're going to have to understand

00:10:16.940 --> 00:10:23.500
how we can make sure that we are distributing things like AI in some equitable manner.

00:10:24.059 --> 00:10:28.619
In insurance, this is a real big problem, especially in the industry that I'm in.

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:33.900
We have a lot of small carriers out there, but they don't have any of the data.

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:39.820
There are about five or six or seven very large carriers that beat all of the small

00:10:39.820 --> 00:10:42.460
carriers up with data, okay?

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:44.299
Now, we're not talking about large language models.

00:10:44.299 --> 00:10:46.380
We're literally just talking about simple GLMs.

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:50.059
We're talking about any of the normal machine learning algorithms, whether they be gradient

00:10:50.059 --> 00:10:56.299
boosting, whether they be random forest, whether they be other elastic nets or tree

00:10:56.299 --> 00:10:57.580
models, it doesn't really matter.

00:10:58.219 --> 00:11:01.260
Whoever has the most data wins, usually in insurance, right?

00:11:01.260 --> 00:11:02.859
In insurance, it's a little bit weird.

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:08.140
We have a zero point inflation on all of the distributions that we're looking at.

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:14.460
So in most cases, when you look at an insurance policy, about 75% to 97% of the time, the

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:16.539
right answer is zero, right?

00:11:16.539 --> 00:11:17.820
People just don't have losses.

00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:21.659
But when they have losses, some of them can be very significant, and they can really hurt

00:11:21.659 --> 00:11:23.659
businesses, they can hurt individuals.

00:11:23.659 --> 00:11:25.419
And that's what insurance is for, right?

00:11:25.419 --> 00:11:30.700
Insurance is for that highly unlikely event that is catastrophic, right?

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:32.859
That's where insurance really helps society.

00:11:32.859 --> 00:11:36.219
And at the end of the day, that's a really interesting problem to solve for a lot of

00:11:36.219 --> 00:11:37.500
data scientists, right?

00:11:38.059 --> 00:11:42.700
The issue is that most of the carriers that are out there that aren't the big national

00:11:42.700 --> 00:11:46.140
guys don't have enough data in order to do that, right?

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:51.419
And that's a big problem because you can use that to your advantage to become a monopoly.

00:11:51.419 --> 00:11:55.179
And if you see Hartford, if you see Travelers, if you see Liberty Mutual, if you see Swiss

00:11:55.179 --> 00:11:58.059
Re or some of the large reinsurers, they have all the data.

00:11:59.099 --> 00:12:03.820
So they can almost always build better models, because at this point, the algorithm doesn't

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:07.820
matter as much as how much data you have and the integrity of that data, right?

00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:12.940
It's really important to understand your problem space and to think very deeply about that

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:15.659
problem space and where you can go get data in order to solve that problem space.

00:12:15.659 --> 00:12:20.780
And so at Valen Analytics, when I was there, we actually created a consortium data set,

00:12:20.780 --> 00:12:23.179
and that was specifically for small carriers.

00:12:23.179 --> 00:12:28.539
It was to allow small carriers and new entrants to the insurance market to be able to take

00:12:28.539 --> 00:12:34.059
advantage of large data sets with people who had subject matter expertise and data science

00:12:34.059 --> 00:12:40.059
expertise to be able to deploy models for those small carriers and democratize the insurance

00:12:40.059 --> 00:12:44.059
base to really allow new entrants and innovation into that space.

00:12:44.059 --> 00:12:48.539
If anybody knows anything about the insurance space now, the one thing that is very, very

00:12:48.539 --> 00:12:53.179
clear is that it is probably one of the slowest moving industries on the planet.

00:12:53.179 --> 00:12:56.859
And the reason that it's one of the slowest moving industries on the planet is because

00:12:56.859 --> 00:12:59.580
there are five carriers that hold all the data and they don't have to move.

00:13:00.299 --> 00:13:03.099
They already have a durable advantage over everybody else.

00:13:03.099 --> 00:13:05.419
And so they're not really interested in innovating.

00:13:05.419 --> 00:13:10.299
Now, that's changed in the last decade quite a bit because of people like Valen and other

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:15.020
software as a service companies that are coming out or data science as a service company that

00:13:15.020 --> 00:13:21.340
are building consortium data sets or finding novel ways to use public source data in order

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:28.299
to create large, either empirical or synthetic data sets that can bring value to bear for

00:13:28.299 --> 00:13:33.020
some of these smaller carriers and allow new entrants into the industry.

00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:36.460
And what I think that's going to do is, first of all, it's going to disrupt the industry.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:41.659
That's why the insurance industry has coined a new term called insure tech, right?

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:45.260
Most of those insure tech companies are not just tech.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:50.299
They should call it like insure data or insure machine learning or insure AI, because that's

00:13:50.299 --> 00:13:52.140
really what all of the insure techs are doing.

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:53.260
They're using AI.

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:54.460
They're using machine learning.

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:55.580
It's really not AI.

00:13:55.580 --> 00:13:56.700
It's machine learning, right?

00:13:57.580 --> 00:14:04.460
It's building models on large consortium or synthetic data sets in order to extract or

00:14:04.460 --> 00:14:06.140
provide that value to smaller carriers.

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:10.619
So they can compete with the big guys, because most of the small guys either just sort of

00:14:10.619 --> 00:14:16.059
lagger along, like barely soldier on through the snow in Siberia, right?

00:14:16.059 --> 00:14:19.739
Or they just get subsumed or bought or acquired by some of the large guys.

00:14:19.739 --> 00:14:22.539
And so they just get bigger and they continue their monopoly.

00:14:22.539 --> 00:14:28.059
What I'm really interested in is making sure that data science and large available data

00:14:28.059 --> 00:14:32.859
sets can actually democratize the industry that I'm in, because I believe it's an unfair

00:14:32.859 --> 00:14:33.260
industry.

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:39.500
And I believe it's a quasi cabal of monopolists that are actually controlling this industry.

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:42.380
And that is true in many, many industries.

00:14:42.380 --> 00:14:47.580
And I think there's going to be a huge opportunity, especially with the advent of chat GPT

00:14:47.580 --> 00:14:55.099
and these LLMs, for software as a service companies to go out and very easily get customers

00:14:55.099 --> 00:15:01.580
in order to optimize those standardized LLMs and do other data science and machine learning

00:15:01.580 --> 00:15:06.619
projects for these companies, deploy those models for them, and allow them to hit those

00:15:06.619 --> 00:15:09.500
models with APIs and bring that value to bear.

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:14.380
Now, there's a lot more insurance companies that are looking to create data science practices

00:15:14.380 --> 00:15:16.219
inside of their own carriers.

00:15:16.219 --> 00:15:20.380
The biggest issue is you have to get a critical mass of data in order to do that.

00:15:20.380 --> 00:15:25.419
I mean, Pi is running $350 million in premium a year, and we don't have enough data.

00:15:25.419 --> 00:15:30.299
We actually had to go to Valen to purchase additional consortium data in order to build a

00:15:30.299 --> 00:15:33.260
robust model, right, because of that zero point mass.

00:15:33.260 --> 00:15:37.260
So you have to be not just a slightly big insurance company, you have to be about a

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:41.500
six, $700 million insurance company that's been writing for three to five years at that

00:15:41.500 --> 00:15:44.780
level in order to have enough data to build a really robust model.

00:15:44.780 --> 00:15:49.820
And so that's where I think using consortium datasets or novel datasets or even some of

00:15:49.820 --> 00:15:57.739
these new algorithms like adversarial algorithms to create synthetic datasets that are very

00:15:57.739 --> 00:16:03.419
closely mirrored to the underlying empirical data to be able to bootstrap and expand that

00:16:03.419 --> 00:16:05.659
data to be able to make more robust models.

00:16:06.299 --> 00:16:09.500
There's a lot of companies that I've talked to that are coming out with things like that,

00:16:10.059 --> 00:16:14.299
and Pi is actively doing a lot of POCs with those types of companies to find out whether

00:16:14.299 --> 00:16:18.380
we can take our smaller dataset and we can exponentiate that dataset so that we have

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:20.380
a much larger dataset to be able to build models on.

00:16:21.580 --> 00:16:22.460
Really interesting.

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:23.340
Thank you.

00:16:23.340 --> 00:16:27.099
I see Liz had a question, a follow-up question in the chat.

00:16:27.099 --> 00:16:28.380
Liz, do you want to jump in here?

00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:31.200
Sure.

00:16:32.299 --> 00:16:36.780
So I worked in the casualty space as an analyst for five years.

00:16:36.780 --> 00:16:42.460
I'm actually about to have an interview next week for a junior data scientist role

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:43.979
trying to get back in the space.

00:16:45.260 --> 00:16:51.500
But I was curious, regarding CHAT-GPT, I think, you know, there's a lot of people doing like

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:57.340
paraprogramming and stuff with that, and they maybe don't realize that when they submit

00:16:57.340 --> 00:17:05.339
a question or a prompt to CHAT-GBT, if it's not a locally hosted LLM, that the host is

00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:11.500
owning that data, whether they're allowed to or not, and that creates a huge exposure.

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:17.339
I'm curious if you have any thoughts or comments about that liability and that exposure.

00:17:17.339 --> 00:17:19.660
Yeah, that's actually a massive liability.

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:27.579
And I don't think that the insurance space is going to capitalize on CHAT-GPT,

00:17:27.579 --> 00:17:34.939
especially in the pricing and underwriting domain, until there is assurances that the

00:17:34.939 --> 00:17:41.900
data that they put in to train specific instances of the LLM are going to be protected in some way

00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:45.420
and cordoned off from the larger language model.

00:17:45.420 --> 00:17:50.619
So right now, I know that there are several companies that I'm working with are like,

00:17:50.619 --> 00:17:55.500
well, we don't want to do anything until we have absolute assurance that our data is safe

00:17:55.500 --> 00:18:01.900
and that no one else can gain any advantage through the use of us putting that data into,

00:18:02.780 --> 00:18:07.500
right, some container or some space that allows us to train those LLMs.

00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:13.420
And I think that is where a lot of new companies are going to be extremely successful,

00:18:13.420 --> 00:18:19.979
is going to be prompt engineering and specialization of those larger language models,

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:24.780
sort of the base model, and making sure that they're doing that in such a way

00:18:24.780 --> 00:18:28.380
that they can make sure that they have an understanding of the custody of the data

00:18:28.380 --> 00:18:33.339
and that they can either tokenize that data or make sure that that data doesn't get

00:18:33.339 --> 00:18:39.180
into sort of the larger pool of data that's being used in order to optimize the underlying base LLM.

00:18:39.180 --> 00:18:40.699
It's really important.

00:18:40.699 --> 00:18:44.459
I think until that happens, Chad GPT is going to be used more for,

00:18:46.619 --> 00:18:52.459
in insurance, it's going to be used for automating processes around changing policies,

00:18:52.459 --> 00:18:56.780
right, making sure that the language and the chat functionality goes back and forth

00:18:56.780 --> 00:18:59.099
very smoothly without any human intervention.

00:18:59.099 --> 00:19:02.459
But I don't think that, you know, it's really going to,

00:19:02.459 --> 00:19:07.500
the insurance industry is really going to capitalize on Chad GPT as an underwriting agent,

00:19:07.500 --> 00:19:13.819
right, until all of that data can, you know, is safe and is completely separated

00:19:13.819 --> 00:19:16.540
and mutually exclusive from the larger pool of data.

00:19:16.540 --> 00:19:18.780
That's going to be a really important piece of the puzzle

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:21.339
that some of these software as a service companies are going to have to figure out.

00:19:23.339 --> 00:19:27.099
I mean, I know that I've already told my team at Pi,

00:19:27.819 --> 00:19:31.500
and I've worked with several other carriers, and I've told them all,

00:19:31.500 --> 00:19:35.579
don't put your data into Chad GPT right now because then everybody gets to use it, right?

00:19:35.579 --> 00:19:36.699
Like this, this thing learns.

00:19:37.260 --> 00:19:42.619
And it's like, you know, it's also about like work product and stuff, you know.

00:19:42.619 --> 00:19:43.579
Oh, totally.

00:19:43.579 --> 00:19:47.739
They, if you, if you say, oh, hey, I need help fixing this, you know,

00:19:47.739 --> 00:19:51.579
chain ladder model or whatever, but you have a little bit of secret sauce in there

00:19:51.579 --> 00:19:55.020
and then someone else asks and then boom, your secrets out and you lose an edge.

00:19:55.660 --> 00:19:56.459
That's exactly right.

00:19:56.459 --> 00:20:02.140
I mean, even in our business, we have a very specialized transformation of the target space

00:20:02.140 --> 00:20:05.260
that we use for our line of business, workers' compensation.

00:20:05.339 --> 00:20:07.339
And we don't want anybody to know that.

00:20:07.339 --> 00:20:09.260
That's a specialized transformation.

00:20:09.260 --> 00:20:11.420
I haven't seen anybody else in the industry use.

00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:12.619
It works really, really well.

00:20:13.260 --> 00:20:15.819
I don't want to give that information to anybody, right?

00:20:16.619 --> 00:20:20.619
And the second I pop it in there, it's possible for someone to extract that.

00:20:22.300 --> 00:20:29.339
Unless new technology and updated knowledge is actually given to the insurance industry

00:20:29.339 --> 00:20:33.900
by some of, you know, a new company, a new individual that's working with these companies

00:20:33.900 --> 00:20:39.260
that actually understands how to specialize these LLMs without delivering the data to

00:20:39.260 --> 00:20:40.459
the larger baseline model.

00:20:41.819 --> 00:20:45.180
I personally don't know how to do that yet, but that, I know that that's something that's

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:48.699
being talked about very actively and heavily within the insurance space.

00:20:48.699 --> 00:20:50.219
It's, well, how do we take advantage of this?

00:20:50.219 --> 00:20:54.380
And if we're going to take advantage of this, how do we not give away our secret sauce

00:20:55.260 --> 00:20:57.500
and take advantage of it at the same time?

00:20:57.979 --> 00:21:03.979
Like from my perspective, it seems like the best use would be like having a privately

00:21:03.979 --> 00:21:11.099
hosted LLM that serves as like a communication agent for people filing claims or whatever

00:21:11.099 --> 00:21:13.979
and their apps, you know, where it's kind of low stakes.

00:21:13.979 --> 00:21:19.739
You can segment the data, make sure it doesn't get out, but you also have like clear, knowledgeable

00:21:19.739 --> 00:21:23.579
communication happening that's automated and understandable.

00:21:23.579 --> 00:21:29.260
And the higher end stuff, like, you know, maybe we'll get there, but that's like pretty

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:30.140
not there right now.

00:21:30.780 --> 00:21:32.140
I think that's exactly right.

00:21:32.140 --> 00:21:37.339
The other big piece of the puzzle that is going to be there is right now, almost all

00:21:37.339 --> 00:21:45.260
insurance companies are, all insurance companies that are using machine learning are using

00:21:45.260 --> 00:21:50.380
it in order to straight through process some accounts, but there's always a human being

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:51.579
overlay, right?

00:21:51.579 --> 00:21:55.739
So you allow the model to make about 30 to 50% of your decisions.

00:21:55.739 --> 00:22:00.699
And then the other 50% of the decisions, 50 to, let's say 30% of the decisions are sent

00:22:00.699 --> 00:22:05.579
to an individual underwriter in the world in order to make a human decision, right?

00:22:05.579 --> 00:22:11.979
With the advent of LLMs, a lot of that need to have a human individual in the mix goes

00:22:11.979 --> 00:22:13.339
away, right?

00:22:13.339 --> 00:22:15.500
Or gets pushed back in the funnel.

00:22:15.500 --> 00:22:19.099
So you can allow a machine learning model, right?

00:22:19.099 --> 00:22:24.300
Which is, which is highly calibrated and constrained, right?

00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:25.979
And then you, here's the trick.

00:22:25.979 --> 00:22:31.660
You get to blend that together with an LLM that is highly specified and constrained and

00:22:31.660 --> 00:22:35.500
optimized so that those two pieces of the puzzle work together, right?

00:22:35.500 --> 00:22:41.339
And then you can remove the underwriter and use them after the decision is made as a check,

00:22:41.339 --> 00:22:41.979
right?

00:22:41.979 --> 00:22:46.540
So you've got a human in the loop who is essentially making sure that the decision,

00:22:46.540 --> 00:22:49.099
you know, didn't have any gaps in it, right?

00:22:49.099 --> 00:22:53.660
Or a human that can identify the gaps that exist in the system so that you can improve

00:22:53.660 --> 00:22:54.140
the system.

00:22:54.140 --> 00:22:58.300
Eventually, what you get to is that maybe you've got a human that needs to be involved,

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:03.020
you know, 5% of the time instead of a human that needs to be involved 50% of the time.

00:23:03.020 --> 00:23:07.500
And the decisions are more consistent and create more separation between the good risk

00:23:07.500 --> 00:23:09.739
and the bad risk, right?

00:23:09.739 --> 00:23:12.380
Now, the other big piece of that puzzle is, is equitability.

00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:18.380
So, you know, are you treating everyone the same across the parameters that matter, right?

00:23:18.380 --> 00:23:21.900
Whether it's demographic, whether it's race, whether it's something else, you've got to

00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:26.540
make sure that you've got a human in there that is making sure that the AI, the LLM and,

00:23:27.500 --> 00:23:34.619
you know, the GLM or the machine learning models are actually not introducing some specific

00:23:34.619 --> 00:23:36.140
bias into the overall solution.

00:23:36.219 --> 00:23:41.739
That was actually one of the anonymous Slido questions was, how do you ensure that bias

00:23:41.739 --> 00:23:45.099
is not introduced when generating synthetic data?

00:23:45.099 --> 00:23:50.619
So it's, it's an awesome question and it depends on what you mean by bias, right?

00:23:50.619 --> 00:23:55.500
Because there's bias, whether it's statistical bias or some other bias inherent in every

00:23:55.500 --> 00:23:57.500
single model that's built, right?

00:23:57.500 --> 00:24:03.900
What we try and do is we, we look very closely at the variables that are going into all of

00:24:03.900 --> 00:24:07.099
our models and that's what's really hard to do with an LLM.

00:24:07.099 --> 00:24:11.099
I mean, you know, somebody else almost has to make sure that there's no bias in the,

00:24:11.099 --> 00:24:15.260
in the baseline LLM, but it's all about the covariates.

00:24:15.260 --> 00:24:18.459
So when we're building a machine learning model, we're taking a look at the covariates

00:24:19.099 --> 00:24:23.099
and we're making sure that those covariates are highly empirical and that they're based

00:24:23.099 --> 00:24:27.020
on, you know, insurance data for the most part.

00:24:27.020 --> 00:24:31.260
Now, there's a lot of demographic data that can come in, especially in the line of business

00:24:31.260 --> 00:24:33.099
that I'm in, which is workers' compensation.

00:24:33.979 --> 00:24:38.380
If anybody doesn't know what workers' compensation is, it's essentially a coverage that

00:24:39.339 --> 00:24:45.660
employers buy so that their employees are covered if they have an accident and it pays

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:50.780
for all of the medical bills plus their, their weekly wage, as long as they cannot get back

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:52.459
to work at the, at the same role, right?

00:24:53.819 --> 00:24:57.020
And when, when you think about that, there's a lot of demographics that come in.

00:24:57.020 --> 00:25:00.219
Things like average household size are actually important.

00:25:00.859 --> 00:25:05.900
Oddly, average hail size is important and you can't imagine what kind of biases that

00:25:05.900 --> 00:25:06.939
actually introduces.

00:25:06.939 --> 00:25:10.619
So if you're a homeowner's insurer, average hail size really matters, right?

00:25:10.619 --> 00:25:12.939
Like the people in Colorado, right?

00:25:12.939 --> 00:25:18.380
They have higher premiums than the people in North Dakota because North Dakota has less

00:25:18.380 --> 00:25:20.140
hail than Colorado does, right?

00:25:20.140 --> 00:25:23.979
Washington has less hail than Colorado does, whereas Washington has different problems,

00:25:23.979 --> 00:25:24.140
right?

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:25.660
They have floods and things like that.

00:25:25.660 --> 00:25:28.939
California is highly biased because of other things.

00:25:28.939 --> 00:25:35.660
But what, what you really care about is, okay, is there some group of people that already

00:25:35.660 --> 00:25:36.459
have it tough?

00:25:36.459 --> 00:25:39.979
And are we making it more tough because of something that's inherent in a covariate that

00:25:39.979 --> 00:25:44.140
we're using that just makes it more difficult for those people to purchase workers'

00:25:44.140 --> 00:25:45.339
compensation insurance?

00:25:45.339 --> 00:25:49.900
We try as best as we can to remove those variables, whether it's average wage, average

00:25:49.900 --> 00:25:55.660
household, any race demographics, anything like that is completely just dumped out of

00:25:55.660 --> 00:25:58.140
our data set right at the beginning, even though those exist.

00:25:58.939 --> 00:25:59.180
Right?

00:26:01.020 --> 00:26:04.540
And so we do our best to try and minimize those biases.

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:10.939
But again, there's always going to be inherent and potentially unknown or unknowable biases

00:26:10.939 --> 00:26:15.339
that actually exist within an overall algorithm estimation.

00:26:15.339 --> 00:26:17.739
So we do the best that we can.

00:26:17.739 --> 00:26:19.420
Nobody's perfect at this.

00:26:20.380 --> 00:26:24.140
There's a lot of new companies that are coming out with novel data like behavioral data.

00:26:24.140 --> 00:26:27.739
And that's something that the industry is talking about very, very closely, right?

00:26:27.739 --> 00:26:34.140
It's like, hey, if we can capture what your media content consumption is, right, and that

00:26:34.140 --> 00:26:40.219
has a significant risk separation between the good risk and the bad risk, is it highly

00:26:40.219 --> 00:26:41.979
correlated with things like race?

00:26:41.979 --> 00:26:43.579
Is it highly correlated with other things?

00:26:43.579 --> 00:26:49.979
Because it may be the case that people of different backgrounds consume different media.

00:26:49.979 --> 00:26:55.500
And that may inherently have some sort of correlation to things that kind of matter

00:26:55.500 --> 00:27:04.699
with regard to the current Zeitgeist in terms of which groups are having trouble and which

00:27:04.699 --> 00:27:05.500
groups aren't.

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:05.739
Right?

00:27:07.339 --> 00:27:08.780
And so there's a lot of conversation there.

00:27:10.219 --> 00:27:10.859
Definitely.

00:27:10.859 --> 00:27:13.819
I see a lot of great questions coming into the chat.

00:27:13.819 --> 00:27:16.619
So I want to make sure I get to some of these, too.

00:27:16.619 --> 00:27:18.060
I'll be more concise.

00:27:18.060 --> 00:27:19.020
No, no, no.

00:27:19.020 --> 00:27:19.500
These are great.

00:27:19.500 --> 00:27:20.699
This is a great discussion.

00:27:20.699 --> 00:27:23.420
I just want to make sure I get some of these, too.

00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:27.739
But Anders, I see you had asked a question a bit earlier in the chat.

00:27:27.739 --> 00:27:28.780
Do you want to jump in here?

00:27:30.699 --> 00:27:32.780
I think you largely answered it, Matt.

00:27:32.780 --> 00:27:36.540
But I was just really interested when I went shopping for life insurance recently that

00:27:37.099 --> 00:27:41.819
there were some companies that were not the biggest companies that were able to do everything

00:27:41.819 --> 00:27:46.619
instantly online and didn't require things like blood draws or physicals or any of that kind of

00:27:46.619 --> 00:27:48.140
like physical evidence.

00:27:48.140 --> 00:27:51.739
And I was assuming that that was because they are using their models.

00:27:51.739 --> 00:27:56.540
Or is it just because they are big enough that they can kind of like marginalize and

00:27:56.540 --> 00:27:57.819
don't need to be that specific?

00:27:57.819 --> 00:28:01.900
I'm just curious what sets up one company to be able to do that and one not to be able

00:28:01.900 --> 00:28:02.380
to do that.

00:28:03.260 --> 00:28:05.900
There's a lot of moving pieces there.

00:28:05.900 --> 00:28:10.619
So generally speaking, what I would say is those people who are doing it online, their

00:28:10.619 --> 00:28:12.780
overall rate level is a little bit higher.

00:28:12.780 --> 00:28:13.020
Right?

00:28:13.020 --> 00:28:16.140
Because they don't have all of the data that some of the larger people who are not doing

00:28:16.140 --> 00:28:17.500
it online actually have.

00:28:17.500 --> 00:28:20.380
And so let's hear an extremely healthy individual.

00:28:20.939 --> 00:28:21.579
OK?

00:28:21.579 --> 00:28:23.900
You have no medical biomarkers.

00:28:23.900 --> 00:28:29.579
You have gone to some company and gotten a very extensive blood draw done, and you have

00:28:29.579 --> 00:28:31.739
a really good understanding of how healthy you are.

00:28:31.739 --> 00:28:32.219
Right?

00:28:32.219 --> 00:28:37.339
You're very likely going to get a better rate with a large company who's not online than

00:28:37.339 --> 00:28:39.099
a smaller company who's online.

00:28:39.099 --> 00:28:44.619
Having said that, smaller companies are using more novel data than the older companies are

00:28:45.260 --> 00:28:51.020
in order to be able to allow consumers to purchase those types of products online.

00:28:51.020 --> 00:28:52.859
And the rate level isn't that different.

00:28:53.420 --> 00:28:53.819
Right?

00:28:53.819 --> 00:28:58.219
You are going to get a discount if you get your blood drawn and do the whole thing if

00:28:58.219 --> 00:29:00.540
you have extremely good biomarkers.

00:29:00.540 --> 00:29:01.099
Right?

00:29:01.099 --> 00:29:05.819
But if you don't have extremely good biomarkers, it's probably the best choice for you to go

00:29:05.819 --> 00:29:09.099
online and just get the policy because they're going to look at completely different stuff.

00:29:09.099 --> 00:29:13.339
Now, you have to understand that a lot of those life insurance companies are also grabbing

00:29:15.020 --> 00:29:19.260
a lot of that data that many of us don't even know they're grabbing.

00:29:19.260 --> 00:29:19.819
Right?

00:29:19.819 --> 00:29:28.699
So purchasing patterns, media content, consumption trends, behavioral trends, these kinds of

00:29:28.699 --> 00:29:30.219
things that they can actually grab.

00:29:30.219 --> 00:29:33.739
So they're using your digital fingerprint a heck of a lot more than they're using your

00:29:33.739 --> 00:29:34.699
biomarkers.

00:29:34.699 --> 00:29:34.939
Right?

00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:39.420
And so you're going to get a higher rate, but they can still do a really good job of

00:29:39.420 --> 00:29:44.540
separating risk, finding out whether you're really interested in drinking a lot of Jack

00:29:44.540 --> 00:29:48.060
Daniels or whether you're really interested in drinking a lot of mushroom tea.

00:29:48.060 --> 00:29:48.300
Right?

00:29:48.300 --> 00:29:51.739
So those are, you know, those are going to be very, very different.

00:29:51.739 --> 00:29:58.859
And companies now can use a lot of these third party API aggregators in order to get all

00:29:58.859 --> 00:30:03.660
of that information and consume that information through deep learning models that are actually

00:30:03.660 --> 00:30:08.540
quite good at separating good life insurance risks from bad life insurance risk.

00:30:11.260 --> 00:30:11.579
Thank you.

00:30:11.579 --> 00:30:12.380
Does that answer your question?

00:30:15.579 --> 00:30:16.459
I see a thumbs up.

00:30:17.339 --> 00:30:21.500
So Arafat had asked a question, you put the star, so I'll read it.

00:30:21.500 --> 00:30:26.060
But it's, the question was, love seeing the energy in your communication.

00:30:26.060 --> 00:30:29.819
Do you have any tips on how we can improve our communication?

00:30:30.380 --> 00:30:34.540
So I have been talking to large groups of people for a very long time.

00:30:36.300 --> 00:30:40.380
When I started, I pictured everybody in their underwear.

00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:41.180
I'm sure you've heard that.

00:30:41.180 --> 00:30:42.380
It's an old trope.

00:30:42.380 --> 00:30:42.619
Right?

00:30:43.099 --> 00:30:48.859
But I think one of the most important things to understand about people in general is we

00:30:48.859 --> 00:30:50.619
all put our underwear on the same way.

00:30:50.619 --> 00:30:55.660
We all take a, you know, we all take a number two and a number one in exactly the same way.

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:56.140
Okay.

00:30:58.140 --> 00:31:04.219
I very early in my career was able to essentially come right out of college.

00:31:04.219 --> 00:31:08.939
And I got an underwriting position at an insurance company that was very small.

00:31:08.939 --> 00:31:10.699
I was employee number five.

00:31:10.780 --> 00:31:15.979
And so I had direct access to the CEO since I was right out of college.

00:31:15.979 --> 00:31:19.739
So my working environment did not include any social hierarchy.

00:31:19.739 --> 00:31:20.859
Like everything was flat.

00:31:21.500 --> 00:31:26.380
And so that's what I would encourage all of you to do is if you're really going to speak

00:31:26.380 --> 00:31:35.660
your truth, you have to be able to punch through the imposter syndrome that you might have,

00:31:36.219 --> 00:31:40.699
the impression of a social hierarchy that you might have.

00:31:40.699 --> 00:31:45.099
You have to be able to talk to a board member or a CEO in the same way that you would talk

00:31:45.099 --> 00:31:47.260
to a colleague because we're all the same.

00:31:47.260 --> 00:31:48.219
We're all humans.

00:31:48.939 --> 00:31:50.219
We all have the same needs.

00:31:51.020 --> 00:31:54.380
And, you know, maybe some people are smarter than others.

00:31:54.380 --> 00:31:55.500
And okay, that's fine.

00:31:55.500 --> 00:31:55.900
Right?

00:31:55.900 --> 00:31:59.260
But if you really want to do a good job of communicating, you have to communicate on

00:31:59.260 --> 00:32:03.579
the same level as another individual, which means you have to assume that you are on the

00:32:03.660 --> 00:32:05.739
same level as the other individual.

00:32:05.739 --> 00:32:09.420
I would just encourage everybody to understand that we're all human beings.

00:32:09.420 --> 00:32:10.859
We all have our foibles.

00:32:11.660 --> 00:32:15.979
You know, there's something that's running around on LinkedIn right now, and it is you

00:32:15.979 --> 00:32:22.699
have to make sure that you are really open and that you're listening to other human beings,

00:32:22.699 --> 00:32:25.339
not just what they're saying, but how they're saying it.

00:32:25.339 --> 00:32:31.660
And the important reason for that is that in anyone's life, any other human being only

00:32:31.660 --> 00:32:34.939
knows about one to two percent of what's going on in their life.

00:32:35.579 --> 00:32:35.819
Right?

00:32:37.500 --> 00:32:42.380
And so I would just really encourage you to empathize and consider yourself on exactly

00:32:42.380 --> 00:32:45.420
the same level as the people that you're talking to.

00:32:45.420 --> 00:32:49.979
And it doesn't matter whether they're a manager, a senior manager, a director, a VP,

00:32:49.979 --> 00:32:53.739
or a C-level employee, or even a board member or an investor.

00:32:53.739 --> 00:32:58.859
If you talk to them as if you are on their same level and they're on your same level,

00:32:58.859 --> 00:33:00.540
you will get better responses.

00:33:00.540 --> 00:33:01.339
I promise you.

00:33:01.339 --> 00:33:02.540
You'll get better responses.

00:33:03.099 --> 00:33:07.819
And I know it's easy to say, and it's a lot harder to do because that anxiety comes up.

00:33:09.339 --> 00:33:11.660
If that anxiety comes up, picture them in their underwear.

00:33:11.660 --> 00:33:14.619
Understand that they take a crap just like the rest of us, right?

00:33:14.619 --> 00:33:15.819
And they've got their own problems.

00:33:17.420 --> 00:33:20.140
I got where I got because I was lucky.

00:33:20.140 --> 00:33:22.060
I made a couple of the right choices.

00:33:22.060 --> 00:33:26.780
And I think probably 90 percent of the people that are actually in positions like mine,

00:33:26.780 --> 00:33:29.180
they got there through dedication.

00:33:29.180 --> 00:33:34.699
They got there through making sure that they were very consistent at a couple of things

00:33:34.699 --> 00:33:39.020
that made sure that they were a person that could be trusted and that they were a person

00:33:39.020 --> 00:33:40.939
that could be counted on, right?

00:33:40.939 --> 00:33:46.140
So doing those small things every single day is going to do wonders for you.

00:33:46.140 --> 00:33:51.339
Now, it's great if you come up with a Svengali move and you come up with the greatest thing

00:33:51.339 --> 00:33:53.500
that the company has ever seen, right?

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:55.260
That's sort of an added bonus.

00:33:55.260 --> 00:33:59.020
But where you win is doing small, consistent things every single day and talking to

00:33:59.020 --> 00:34:04.699
everyone like they're a brother or like they're a sister and making sure that you are really

00:34:04.699 --> 00:34:10.459
empathizing with them and that they know that you have the company's interest at heart,

00:34:10.459 --> 00:34:14.139
that you have their interest at heart, and that you're listening to what their needs

00:34:14.139 --> 00:34:14.379
are.

00:34:14.379 --> 00:34:19.179
If you can do that, then you will become much more confident in how you speak very, very

00:34:19.179 --> 00:34:19.739
quickly.

00:34:19.739 --> 00:34:22.060
Now, I will say I've got a lot of bombast, too.

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:26.300
My wife tells me again and again that I'm the only person she's ever met that doesn't

00:34:26.300 --> 00:34:28.699
give a crap what anybody else says about them.

00:34:28.699 --> 00:34:30.300
And that's completely true.

00:34:30.300 --> 00:34:32.780
I just don't worry about my image that much.

00:34:32.780 --> 00:34:34.379
I worry about being a good human.

00:34:35.179 --> 00:34:39.260
I don't worry about being a pretty human or professional human or the smartest human on

00:34:39.260 --> 00:34:39.659
the planet.

00:34:39.659 --> 00:34:44.780
I just worry about being a good human that people can trust and that people can count

00:34:44.780 --> 00:34:45.500
on.

00:34:45.500 --> 00:34:46.060
And that's it.

00:34:48.219 --> 00:34:52.139
What you just said about like doing those small, consistent things was reminding me of

00:34:52.139 --> 00:34:58.620
that video I saw you just posted on LinkedIn about like being an effective leader isn't

00:34:58.620 --> 00:35:04.780
just like going to the leadership workshop one time a year and saying, OK, well, I'm

00:35:04.780 --> 00:35:06.540
trained on being a leader.

00:35:07.580 --> 00:35:13.820
And so I was also wondering, what are other things that you think make someone an

00:35:13.820 --> 00:35:15.100
effective leader?

00:35:17.659 --> 00:35:21.179
So there's a couple of things that I post on LinkedIn.

00:35:21.179 --> 00:35:22.300
Some of them are quite old.

00:35:22.860 --> 00:35:26.620
There was one that I posted that, and I'm sure everybody's seen this, the difference

00:35:26.620 --> 00:35:29.340
between a boss and a leader, right?

00:35:30.620 --> 00:35:35.580
A boss sits behind you with a whip and yells at you to get stuff done.

00:35:36.139 --> 00:35:39.100
And a leader is the one who's pulling you along.

00:35:39.100 --> 00:35:46.459
He's or she is the one who is removing the blocks, who is actually serving the employees.

00:35:46.459 --> 00:35:52.540
And I consider myself and I'm a strong believer in servant leadership, right?

00:35:52.540 --> 00:35:54.459
I'm not anybody's boss.

00:35:54.459 --> 00:36:00.219
I am the person who is responsible for making sure that all of the conditions are set up

00:36:00.219 --> 00:36:07.899
so that each and every one of my employees can succeed and can fully explore the domain

00:36:07.899 --> 00:36:08.860
of their competencies.

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:12.060
That's my job, right?

00:36:12.060 --> 00:36:16.459
My job is to find smart people and then set up the conditions and get the heck out of

00:36:16.459 --> 00:36:17.020
the way.

00:36:17.020 --> 00:36:22.060
And if there's a blocker that is in their way, I need to go find a way to remove that

00:36:22.060 --> 00:36:23.820
blocker, right?

00:36:23.820 --> 00:36:25.820
Now, are there performance reviews and things like that?

00:36:25.820 --> 00:36:27.500
Yeah, every company has them.

00:36:27.500 --> 00:36:29.659
I am a strong proponent against them.

00:36:29.659 --> 00:36:31.500
So I hate performance reviews.

00:36:31.500 --> 00:36:35.340
I think that performance reviews should be done every single day between the individuals

00:36:35.340 --> 00:36:36.540
that are working together.

00:36:36.540 --> 00:36:40.780
And I don't think it should be between a boss and that boss's employees.

00:36:40.780 --> 00:36:45.659
I think it should be the individuals on, that they're colleagues on the team that are working

00:36:45.659 --> 00:36:47.020
together with one another.

00:36:47.020 --> 00:36:48.699
That's where that feedback should be coming from.

00:36:48.699 --> 00:36:54.060
It should be a 360 degree feedback because performance reviews are a thing that can be

00:36:54.060 --> 00:36:55.419
weaponized so easily.

00:36:55.419 --> 00:36:58.620
And they say more about the person who's giving the review than they do about the person who's

00:36:58.620 --> 00:36:59.820
being reviewed, period.

00:37:00.459 --> 00:37:01.580
That is my position.

00:37:01.580 --> 00:37:07.020
Now, I'm happy to argue with anyone about that particular position because of how strongly

00:37:07.020 --> 00:37:08.860
I actually believe in that position.

00:37:08.860 --> 00:37:13.419
I think that if we can create an egalitarian society where everyone is responsible to everyone

00:37:13.419 --> 00:37:18.540
else and everyone is giving constant feedback to everyone else on how to improve with empathy,

00:37:19.260 --> 00:37:24.780
and with honesty, that is where you can create an organization or a social structure and

00:37:24.780 --> 00:37:30.860
a social hierarchy that actually allows everyone to win and allows everyone to succeed and

00:37:30.860 --> 00:37:35.260
allows everyone to explore all of the levels of Maslow's hierarchy, right?

00:37:35.260 --> 00:37:37.500
That's how you become fully human and fully yourself.

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:39.899
Thank you, Matt.

00:37:40.860 --> 00:37:43.820
I promise I will get to some of the other insurance questions.

00:37:43.820 --> 00:37:47.580
And I'm going to be selfish for just a second here and ask a question.

00:37:47.979 --> 00:37:54.780
You said part of the role in a leader is removing some of those blockers for your team.

00:37:54.780 --> 00:38:00.219
And I'm wondering for some of us here who maybe are in a role where we've identified

00:38:00.219 --> 00:38:07.419
certain blockers for us, how would you recommend you go about like sharing that with your

00:38:07.419 --> 00:38:10.939
leadership to kind of get past those roadblocks?

00:38:12.300 --> 00:38:14.780
Whether it's an I or a we, right?

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:19.260
Sometimes there's a blocker for a whole team and sometimes there's a blocker for an individual,

00:38:19.260 --> 00:38:19.899
right?

00:38:19.899 --> 00:38:24.860
I think what you need to do is, I don't know if any of you have taken any courses in nonviolent

00:38:24.860 --> 00:38:25.659
communication.

00:38:25.659 --> 00:38:27.100
It's kind of a big thing now.

00:38:27.100 --> 00:38:29.100
We've taken a lot in nonviolent communication.

00:38:29.659 --> 00:38:33.500
I don't believe all of it, but I think it is a tool set where you can sort of mix and

00:38:33.500 --> 00:38:35.739
match some of the tools that come out of nonviolent communication.

00:38:35.739 --> 00:38:41.500
One of those things is to listen for needs and to express needs, right?

00:38:41.500 --> 00:38:44.939
So you start with, I'm trying to do this for the company.

00:38:45.500 --> 00:38:47.659
I believe that this is going to be very valuable.

00:38:47.659 --> 00:38:48.379
Do you agree?

00:38:49.020 --> 00:38:49.659
Right?

00:38:49.659 --> 00:38:54.139
So first, you've got to get buy-in on what you're trying to do is valuable for the

00:38:54.139 --> 00:38:55.899
organization and valuable for the company.

00:38:55.899 --> 00:38:56.379
Okay?

00:38:56.379 --> 00:39:01.179
The second thing is, in order to do that, I have certain needs that are not being met.

00:39:01.820 --> 00:39:02.219
Okay?

00:39:02.219 --> 00:39:03.500
This is what those needs are.

00:39:03.500 --> 00:39:04.379
It could be an individual.

00:39:04.379 --> 00:39:05.820
It could be a group of individuals.

00:39:05.820 --> 00:39:06.939
It could be a dynamic.

00:39:06.939 --> 00:39:09.580
It could be technology that isn't there.

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:10.139
It could be budget.

00:39:10.139 --> 00:39:11.419
It could be whatever, right?

00:39:11.739 --> 00:39:17.659
And then you really express that as a need, not as a so-and-so is doing something to me

00:39:17.659 --> 00:39:18.379
and I'm mad, right?

00:39:18.379 --> 00:39:21.500
That's a very sort of a selfish communication.

00:39:21.500 --> 00:39:25.340
What you want to do is you want to try to abstract that as much as you can.

00:39:25.340 --> 00:39:29.979
Now, you can't always because sometimes it's just a person who isn't on board, right?

00:39:29.979 --> 00:39:34.699
And so you say, look, I really need this person to be on board, but I don't think this

00:39:34.699 --> 00:39:35.979
person is on board.

00:39:35.979 --> 00:39:43.899
And I want to ask you what we can do together in order to try and identify that other person's

00:39:43.899 --> 00:39:48.939
needs and discover why it is that they appear to be a blocker.

00:39:48.939 --> 00:39:54.300
It may be in my own head and I'm just, you know, I'm just in an echo chamber, but let's

00:39:54.300 --> 00:39:55.739
have that conversation.

00:39:55.739 --> 00:39:59.739
And if you don't feel confident having that conversation yourself, go to someone who you

00:39:59.739 --> 00:40:01.260
think can have that conversation.

00:40:01.260 --> 00:40:02.379
And it doesn't have to be a manager.

00:40:02.379 --> 00:40:07.419
It could be a colleague who knows that person really well and can set up that meeting so

00:40:07.419 --> 00:40:10.699
that you can have that meeting and identify what those needs are.

00:40:10.699 --> 00:40:14.540
There's another book that I would really strongly recommend, and unfortunately it's escaping

00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:15.659
me right now.

00:40:15.659 --> 00:40:17.260
The guy's name is Chris Voss.

00:40:17.260 --> 00:40:18.540
It's called Never Split the Difference.

00:40:18.540 --> 00:40:20.219
I don't know if any of you have read that.

00:40:20.219 --> 00:40:22.060
Strongly encourage you to read that book.

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:24.540
Some of it's throwaway, right?

00:40:24.540 --> 00:40:28.939
But, you know, I follow the Pareto principle, so there's always 20% of, you know, absolutely

00:40:28.939 --> 00:40:30.379
fantastic nuggets in every book.

00:40:30.699 --> 00:40:34.620
So that book basically teaches you to get to know.

00:40:35.739 --> 00:40:39.020
You talk to an individual and you have a dialogue with them.

00:40:39.020 --> 00:40:43.260
You have a dialectic with them until you get to why they're saying no to whatever thing

00:40:43.260 --> 00:40:45.100
you want to get through, right?

00:40:45.100 --> 00:40:48.699
Because yeses that aren't really yeses don't matter.

00:40:48.699 --> 00:40:50.459
You have to get to the no, right?

00:40:50.459 --> 00:40:56.780
And so that I think making sure that you understand what the other person's needs are or the

00:40:56.780 --> 00:40:58.939
organization's needs, if that's a blocker.

00:40:59.020 --> 00:41:02.939
And then making sure that you're constructing the right conversation and you're having those

00:41:02.939 --> 00:41:08.540
conversations through an expression of needs on both sides, a reciprocal expression of

00:41:08.540 --> 00:41:09.179
needs.

00:41:09.179 --> 00:41:13.100
Usually that is the black swan that will bust right through that blocker.

00:41:15.419 --> 00:41:16.060
Amazing.

00:41:16.060 --> 00:41:17.260
Thank you so much, Matt.

00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:18.860
That's incredibly helpful.

00:41:19.979 --> 00:41:20.459
Okay.

00:41:20.459 --> 00:41:22.620
Jumping back over to some of the questions in the chat.

00:41:22.860 --> 00:41:27.739
Alan, I see you had a question around some of the regulatory requirements.

00:41:27.739 --> 00:41:28.780
Do you want to jump in here?

00:41:29.820 --> 00:41:30.379
Yeah, sure.

00:41:30.379 --> 00:41:31.020
Thanks.

00:41:31.020 --> 00:41:32.620
This is really, really interesting today.

00:41:34.620 --> 00:41:39.179
Matt, kind of following on the thread that you started with about these opportunities

00:41:39.179 --> 00:41:41.739
coming from data to democratize this industry.

00:41:41.739 --> 00:41:46.300
I wonder if there's a counterpart regulatory piece that you see.

00:41:46.300 --> 00:41:51.739
Are there regulatory gaps in that being able to be successful in making sure that you're

00:41:51.820 --> 00:41:56.620
successful in this industry that you described as being a monopolistic cabal?

00:41:56.620 --> 00:42:01.500
Are there regulatory things that you think are really important either for consumer protection

00:42:01.500 --> 00:42:09.020
or for pushing back against anti-competitive kind of practices that would make a difference?

00:42:10.219 --> 00:42:10.699
Yes.

00:42:10.699 --> 00:42:15.580
And this is where my opinions are probably the most provocative.

00:42:16.139 --> 00:42:24.860
I believe that, by and large, insurance is massively overregulated.

00:42:24.860 --> 00:42:25.899
Massively.

00:42:25.899 --> 00:42:31.100
To the point that it's actually been regulated in such a way that it's extremely difficult

00:42:31.100 --> 00:42:32.939
for new entrants to get in, right?

00:42:33.739 --> 00:42:38.939
I think we've democratized some of it with a lot of the things that companies like Valen

00:42:38.939 --> 00:42:42.540
have done and other companies constructing consortium data sets.

00:42:42.540 --> 00:42:47.820
But the regulatory world in insurance is extremely antiquated.

00:42:49.659 --> 00:42:54.699
They're basically operating on 1970s principles, by and large, okay?

00:42:54.699 --> 00:43:00.060
And those principles were set up by the insurance industry at that time, which was populated

00:43:00.060 --> 00:43:06.699
by a very few, extremely large carriers, specifically for the purposes of creating

00:43:06.699 --> 00:43:09.260
barriers to entry for new entrants, okay?

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:12.780
So, I believe all of the regulations need to be completely rewritten, and they need

00:43:12.780 --> 00:43:15.979
to be completely rewritten in view of the latest technologies.

00:43:17.260 --> 00:43:23.899
There is something that one has to understand about insurance, and that is that it is an

00:43:23.899 --> 00:43:26.780
asymmetric information game, okay?

00:43:26.780 --> 00:43:31.340
The insurance carrier gets to ask questions, and they have to ask questions mostly through

00:43:31.340 --> 00:43:33.899
a third party, through the insurance agent, right?

00:43:33.899 --> 00:43:39.500
And so, not only do you have information asymmetry, but you have information distortion

00:43:39.500 --> 00:43:40.860
as well.

00:43:40.860 --> 00:43:46.139
And so, what the insurance companies are trying to do is put themselves on a level playing

00:43:46.139 --> 00:43:50.219
field, because the insured has all of the knowledge about what their exposures and what

00:43:50.219 --> 00:43:50.860
the risks are.

00:43:51.500 --> 00:43:56.219
The insurance agent has probably 20% of that information, and the insurance carrier probably

00:43:56.219 --> 00:43:58.300
has about 10% of that information.

00:43:58.300 --> 00:44:04.379
A lot of what's coming available now is actually increasing that 10% to maybe 30%, 35% of the

00:44:04.379 --> 00:44:05.419
information, right?

00:44:05.419 --> 00:44:10.780
There's still unconscientious, disagreeable people out there that are lying about all

00:44:10.780 --> 00:44:11.500
of their information.

00:44:11.500 --> 00:44:16.300
They're a roofer, and they're saying that they're a computer programming company.

00:44:16.939 --> 00:44:19.899
They're a trucker, and they're saying that they're a retail shop, right?

00:44:21.100 --> 00:44:28.219
And that's where models are actually quite good at determining whether someone is actually

00:44:28.219 --> 00:44:29.739
lying to you or not, right?

00:44:29.739 --> 00:44:32.780
And identifying and shaving down the moral hazard.

00:44:32.780 --> 00:44:39.899
Now, having said that, there are still ways now, and will be ways in the future, that

00:44:39.899 --> 00:44:44.860
insurance companies can take advantage of information that the insured doesn't even know

00:44:44.860 --> 00:44:45.899
they have.

00:44:45.899 --> 00:44:50.459
And so, I think that information transparency is a huge piece of the puzzle.

00:44:50.459 --> 00:44:56.300
I think that if an insurance company is making a decision, letting the insured know what

00:44:56.300 --> 00:45:01.500
information they're using in order to render that decision is probably going to be very

00:45:01.500 --> 00:45:02.459
important in the future.

00:45:03.820 --> 00:45:08.620
But I think that the regulations around machine learning and filing models with the

00:45:08.620 --> 00:45:14.139
Department of Insurance and the scrutiny that they have to go through is massively, like

00:45:14.139 --> 00:45:19.260
exponentially slowing down the innovation that could occur in the insurance industry.

00:45:19.260 --> 00:45:23.580
It's also why most insurance companies that I've worked with are choosing not to file

00:45:23.580 --> 00:45:24.139
their models.

00:45:24.139 --> 00:45:27.500
There are very few people that are actually filing models in the commercial insurance

00:45:27.500 --> 00:45:28.060
space.

00:45:28.060 --> 00:45:32.459
In the personal auto space or the personal line space, you have to file all of your models.

00:45:32.459 --> 00:45:34.540
So, the Department of Insurance gets to look at it.

00:45:34.540 --> 00:45:35.659
They get to scrutinize it.

00:45:35.659 --> 00:45:37.820
They can say no on just about anything, and they do.

00:45:38.860 --> 00:45:42.219
And there are some states that don't even allow for trade secret.

00:45:42.219 --> 00:45:45.580
So, once you have to file your model with the Department of Insurance, your competitor

00:45:45.580 --> 00:45:49.500
can actually get all of that information and rebuild your model, which I've done several

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:50.219
times.

00:45:50.219 --> 00:45:55.899
So, I think there needs to be massive changes in regulation around data science, machine

00:45:55.899 --> 00:46:02.620
learning, and algorithms and how they're used in determining pricing and availability of

00:46:02.620 --> 00:46:03.419
insurance coverage.

00:46:04.780 --> 00:46:09.580
But I think it also needs to be in light of the fact that insurance carriers are playing

00:46:09.580 --> 00:46:11.340
an information asymmetric game.

00:46:11.340 --> 00:46:15.500
We do not have as much information as we need in order to render the best possible coverage

00:46:15.500 --> 00:46:18.060
and pricing decision on an individual business.

00:46:18.060 --> 00:46:19.739
And really, that's what we're trying to do.

00:46:19.820 --> 00:46:23.899
We're essentially buying used cars, and we have to figure out whether that used car has

00:46:23.899 --> 00:46:29.580
had something bad that the seller of that used car knows exactly what's going on with

00:46:29.580 --> 00:46:29.899
that car.

00:46:29.899 --> 00:46:31.739
We don't know exactly what's going on with that car.

00:46:31.739 --> 00:46:34.060
And that's what I think most insurance carriers are trying to solve.

00:46:34.060 --> 00:46:36.620
Thanks.

00:46:36.620 --> 00:46:40.300
There's a bunch there that's super interesting and a lot of perspective, especially about

00:46:40.300 --> 00:46:41.580
asymmetric information.

00:46:42.780 --> 00:46:43.739
It's new for me to think about.

00:46:43.739 --> 00:46:44.379
Appreciate hearing it.

00:46:44.379 --> 00:46:45.020
Thank you.

00:46:45.020 --> 00:46:45.500
Absolutely.

00:46:45.500 --> 00:46:49.659
AJ, I see you had a question in the chat as well.

00:46:49.659 --> 00:46:50.620
Do you want to jump in here?

00:46:53.659 --> 00:46:54.540
Sure, yeah.

00:46:54.540 --> 00:47:01.020
I wanted to get your opinion on see how far is some of these job functions being automated,

00:47:01.020 --> 00:47:07.500
such as underwriting or app input, because AI is so much advanced, and it's reading so

00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:10.459
much data from your database, vast databases.

00:47:10.459 --> 00:47:13.179
So your thoughts on that?

00:47:13.179 --> 00:47:16.060
Yeah, so I don't believe that all risks.

00:47:16.060 --> 00:47:24.780
And now with the latest technology, my opinion is changing sort of actively as I start to

00:47:24.780 --> 00:47:29.340
understand a little bit more about these LLMs and transformers and the like.

00:47:31.260 --> 00:47:38.620
I believe that probably 85% to 90%, maybe even 95% of the underwriting decisions that

00:47:38.620 --> 00:47:43.020
are currently being made by human beings in the world will be eliminated through the

00:47:43.020 --> 00:47:45.020
use of machine learning and AI.

00:47:45.020 --> 00:47:46.300
I mean, that's just a simple fact.

00:47:48.060 --> 00:47:53.580
It is already the case that machine learning models can make a significantly better and

00:47:53.580 --> 00:47:57.260
more consistent decision than humans.

00:47:57.260 --> 00:47:59.739
Now, it is game theoretic, right?

00:47:59.739 --> 00:48:07.739
So what the models are not quite as good yet at doing, and obviously there's ways to solve

00:48:07.739 --> 00:48:13.820
this using models, they're not quite as good at understanding the market conditions and

00:48:13.820 --> 00:48:18.139
the changing market conditions with regard to what the best price might be, right?

00:48:19.100 --> 00:48:23.020
Insurance carriers have to be able to understand good risk from bad risk, but they also have

00:48:23.020 --> 00:48:24.780
to write policies, right?

00:48:24.780 --> 00:48:28.459
And that means that sometimes you have to make trade-offs, and that's where human beings

00:48:28.459 --> 00:48:28.780
come in.

00:48:28.780 --> 00:48:29.979
They're making those trade-offs.

00:48:29.979 --> 00:48:33.500
They're saying, well, I might write this at a slightly higher loss ratio, but if I don't

00:48:33.500 --> 00:48:38.860
write this packet of business at a slightly higher loss ratio, I'm not going to have enough

00:48:38.860 --> 00:48:39.979
revenue, right?

00:48:39.979 --> 00:48:45.020
So the game theoretic piece of the puzzle, sort of price optimization, which is a really

00:48:45.020 --> 00:48:49.500
bad word in insurance, but that's how we think, right?

00:48:49.500 --> 00:48:51.739
We're actually doing price optimization every single day.

00:48:51.739 --> 00:48:54.219
It's just that we're doing it through human underwriters.

00:48:54.219 --> 00:48:59.419
I think where the world's going to go in insurance is that a lot of the customer service

00:48:59.419 --> 00:49:04.780
personnel are going to be eliminated because LLMs are going to take on that, you know,

00:49:04.780 --> 00:49:10.459
chatbots and RPA and automation are going to be able to do probably 95 to 100 percent

00:49:10.459 --> 00:49:14.939
of policy changes, endorsements, things like that.

00:49:14.939 --> 00:49:19.979
But on the underwriting side, I think that it will probably eliminate 85 to 90 percent

00:49:19.979 --> 00:49:20.540
of the decisions.

00:49:20.540 --> 00:49:24.860
That doesn't mean that the underwriter's role gets eliminated.

00:49:24.860 --> 00:49:27.820
It means that the underwriter's role changes significantly.

00:49:27.820 --> 00:49:30.540
It changes to a portfolio management role.

00:49:30.540 --> 00:49:33.739
It changes to a gap identification role.

00:49:33.739 --> 00:49:39.100
And it changes to a role where an underwriter is now the subject matter expert that works

00:49:39.100 --> 00:49:45.899
directly with the data science team in order to identify and explore the gaps that may

00:49:45.899 --> 00:49:52.620
exist in the model solutions and helps to fill those with novel data and perspective

00:49:52.620 --> 00:49:56.860
that sometimes a lot of the data science teams don't have because they're not on the front

00:49:56.860 --> 00:49:57.580
lines.

00:49:57.580 --> 00:50:02.300
And that's sort of a surrogate is it is really important in insurance that the data science

00:50:02.300 --> 00:50:06.620
team actually has a working knowledge of the line of business that they're actually looking

00:50:06.620 --> 00:50:06.860
at.

00:50:06.860 --> 00:50:10.939
So if you are building a model for commercial auto, you have to understand commercial auto.

00:50:10.939 --> 00:50:11.979
You have to understand how it's rated.

00:50:11.979 --> 00:50:13.580
You have to understand the coverages, et cetera.

00:50:14.219 --> 00:50:18.939
I have a lot of PhD data scientists that I've worked with in the past that felt like, hey,

00:50:18.939 --> 00:50:19.739
I'm a data scientist.

00:50:19.739 --> 00:50:23.260
I don't need to know the underlying environment.

00:50:23.260 --> 00:50:26.379
I'm just going to grab the data and I'm going to build a model.

00:50:26.379 --> 00:50:31.580
I can tell you that in my experience, 90% of the models that are built in that fashion

00:50:31.580 --> 00:50:34.379
fail because they cannot be productionalized.

00:50:34.379 --> 00:50:38.860
The data scientists didn't find out whether the information was available at the time

00:50:38.860 --> 00:50:44.300
that the decision needed to be made or the target was not transformed in a way that was

00:50:44.300 --> 00:50:48.860
critically important because the data was centered or there was a treatment effect that

00:50:48.860 --> 00:50:51.419
they did not identify until after they built the model.

00:50:51.580 --> 00:50:53.179
They have to rebuild the whole model over again.

00:50:57.020 --> 00:50:57.500
Thank you.

00:50:58.860 --> 00:51:02.860
This is kind of a follow-up question here about talking about building this model.

00:51:02.860 --> 00:51:04.939
There was an anonymous question.

00:51:06.060 --> 00:51:11.179
Can you walk through how your team approaches finding a valuable question, exploring that

00:51:11.179 --> 00:51:17.100
question, building and testing a predictive model, and then deploying that, the technical

00:51:17.100 --> 00:51:17.739
aspect of that?

00:51:19.500 --> 00:51:21.100
I'm going to try and be concise there.

00:51:21.100 --> 00:51:22.219
I'm not sure how concise I can be.

00:51:24.939 --> 00:51:30.620
Generally speaking, we will, on a regular basis, go out to each one of the department

00:51:30.620 --> 00:51:35.419
heads and we will ask them, what are your problems today?

00:51:35.419 --> 00:51:36.860
What is creating too much friction?

00:51:38.060 --> 00:51:42.860
What is something that you think could be a better decision that's being poorly

00:51:42.860 --> 00:51:43.580
decision today?

00:51:44.219 --> 00:51:46.139
Then we'll get all of that information back.

00:51:46.540 --> 00:51:54.219
Once we construct all of the potential opportunities for data science, then we start to

00:51:54.219 --> 00:51:59.500
look around at the available data sources that we have and we start to do some discovery

00:51:59.500 --> 00:52:02.780
around whether or not we can actually solve that particular problem with data.

00:52:02.780 --> 00:52:05.580
Do we have the data available to be able to solve that problem?

00:52:06.219 --> 00:52:08.780
Is that problem a big enough problem to solve?

00:52:09.419 --> 00:52:14.459
Usually, once we go to the department heads, we'll then go to the business or department

00:52:14.459 --> 00:52:18.860
analysts within that particular department and say, hey, how big of a problem is this?

00:52:18.860 --> 00:52:21.260
Can we quantify the friction?

00:52:21.260 --> 00:52:23.340
Can we quantify how much this is costing us?

00:52:23.340 --> 00:52:23.979
How many minutes?

00:52:23.979 --> 00:52:24.620
How many hours?

00:52:24.620 --> 00:52:25.340
How many days?

00:52:25.340 --> 00:52:30.780
How many employee days does this take?

00:52:32.139 --> 00:52:36.379
Theoretically, if we were able to remove that and automate that, what would the savings

00:52:36.379 --> 00:52:36.879
be?

00:52:37.179 --> 00:52:39.739
Then, of course, there's other things in the industry.

00:52:39.739 --> 00:52:43.340
How much better can we make around these decisions?

00:52:44.300 --> 00:52:46.459
Can I separate good risk from bad risk?

00:52:46.459 --> 00:52:49.979
Can I identify the probability that someone's actually going to pay their bills?

00:52:49.979 --> 00:52:53.179
Can I identify the cost if they don't pay their bills?

00:52:53.179 --> 00:52:56.060
Can I identify how many times they're not going to pay their bills and we've got to

00:52:56.060 --> 00:52:59.419
do something with that policy, whether it be to cancel it and reinstate it and all that

00:52:59.419 --> 00:53:01.260
stuff because that costs insurance company money.

00:53:02.379 --> 00:53:04.620
All of those different things, even on the marketing side.

00:53:07.340 --> 00:53:12.939
What's our current customer acquisition cost and where is it relatively high and is there

00:53:12.939 --> 00:53:14.939
a way for us to build a model in order to lower that?

00:53:15.500 --> 00:53:18.459
There's a wide variety of different things that you can do.

00:53:18.459 --> 00:53:22.459
Once you sit on a problem and you know that there's enough value there and you know that

00:53:22.459 --> 00:53:28.939
you have the data to be able to solve that problem, then it's a pretty standard process.

00:53:28.939 --> 00:53:29.899
You have to wrangle the data.

00:53:29.899 --> 00:53:31.100
You have to normalize the data.

00:53:31.100 --> 00:53:36.699
You have to work together with the department experts in that department to identify what

00:53:36.699 --> 00:53:39.899
they think might be interesting or valuable covariates.

00:53:40.860 --> 00:53:45.899
So usually we will do some unsupervised modeling just to figure out what the data looks like.

00:53:46.540 --> 00:53:49.179
Where might there be blooms of data that could be interesting?

00:53:50.139 --> 00:53:54.860
And then we'll do a correlation study, which is with as many covariates that we can actually

00:53:54.860 --> 00:53:59.580
put together and then bring that back to the department and then ask the subject matter

00:53:59.580 --> 00:54:02.540
experts what's not in here that you think should be in here.

00:54:03.260 --> 00:54:07.020
And then they'll start to think about and construct some additional features.

00:54:07.020 --> 00:54:08.699
Then you start the feature engineering phase.

00:54:09.260 --> 00:54:13.659
You do that with the subject matter experts in that department and you try and get as

00:54:13.659 --> 00:54:15.899
many features that you think might be useful as possible.

00:54:17.340 --> 00:54:20.139
And then, of course, there's some target transformation sometimes.

00:54:20.139 --> 00:54:21.739
Are you going to build a logistic model?

00:54:21.739 --> 00:54:22.939
Are you going to build a linear model?

00:54:23.739 --> 00:54:25.979
Are you going to build something that you're going to use for triage?

00:54:26.860 --> 00:54:31.979
Is it going to be sort of a categorical model where you've got five or six different decisions

00:54:31.979 --> 00:54:34.459
that need to be made and you're going to split those up?

00:54:34.459 --> 00:54:37.500
You kind of figure out what the best sort of opportunity is there.

00:54:38.939 --> 00:54:41.580
And then we usually go through a sample and partitioning.

00:54:41.580 --> 00:54:42.699
How are you going to sample this?

00:54:42.699 --> 00:54:44.060
What's your strategy going to be?

00:54:44.860 --> 00:54:46.459
What is your validation strategy?

00:54:46.459 --> 00:54:48.620
So are you going to do cross-fold validation?

00:54:48.620 --> 00:54:49.979
What's your holdout going to look like?

00:54:49.979 --> 00:54:51.419
What's your train set going to look like?

00:54:51.419 --> 00:54:53.340
What's your testing set going to look like?

00:54:53.340 --> 00:54:54.780
Are those stratified correctly?

00:54:55.820 --> 00:54:57.739
Is anything time series based?

00:54:57.739 --> 00:55:02.540
Because that has a significant impact on how you're thinking about your sampling strategy.

00:55:03.419 --> 00:55:09.739
Usually in insurance, depending on data size and the composition of the target,

00:55:09.739 --> 00:55:14.860
we use anywhere between three partitions and 10 partitions.

00:55:15.899 --> 00:55:18.379
If it's a more complicated problem and we've got a lot of data,

00:55:18.379 --> 00:55:21.500
we'll use up to 10 partitions and we'll hold three or four of them out.

00:55:21.500 --> 00:55:25.580
And then we'll use incrementally four or five or six or seven of those

00:55:26.300 --> 00:55:29.820
in order to increment through the overall model building process.

00:55:29.820 --> 00:55:32.780
We'll use the first partition, maybe even split that up

00:55:34.300 --> 00:55:39.659
in order to do feature engineering and basic variable selection and reduction.

00:55:39.659 --> 00:55:44.139
Then we will build our initial model and then we'll test it on the next partition.

00:55:44.139 --> 00:55:46.939
And then normally what we do is we'll build on,

00:55:46.939 --> 00:55:49.020
let's say you have five different partitions.

00:55:49.020 --> 00:55:50.540
We build on one and two, test on three.

00:55:50.540 --> 00:55:51.979
Build on one and three, test on two.

00:55:51.979 --> 00:55:54.139
Build on two and three, test on one, right?

00:55:54.139 --> 00:55:57.659
And then once you're really confident that you've got the right model using that data,

00:55:57.659 --> 00:55:59.100
you add the next partition.

00:55:59.100 --> 00:56:01.340
Now you've got one, two, and three built on four,

00:56:01.340 --> 00:56:03.899
four, three, and two built on, you know,

00:56:03.899 --> 00:56:06.540
tested on one and so on and so forth, right?

00:56:06.540 --> 00:56:09.500
And we're constantly looking at coefficients, whether they're shifting,

00:56:09.500 --> 00:56:11.020
whether they're going up and down.

00:56:11.020 --> 00:56:13.739
If it's a tree model, we're looking at what the splits look like.

00:56:14.620 --> 00:56:19.419
We're sort of doing hyperparameter selection usually on those early partitions

00:56:19.419 --> 00:56:21.100
until you get to the final model,

00:56:21.100 --> 00:56:24.620
usually with two or three validations that's already held out.

00:56:24.620 --> 00:56:27.659
And in insurance, we're usually using between five and eight

00:56:27.659 --> 00:56:30.780
cross-fold validation at each one of those stages,

00:56:30.780 --> 00:56:31.979
just to make sure that we're getting,

00:56:33.739 --> 00:56:37.020
there's a lot of volatility because of the zero point math in insurance.

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:40.219
So you really need to make sure that you've got enough cross-fold validation there

00:56:40.219 --> 00:56:41.899
because you can have a very large loss

00:56:42.699 --> 00:56:45.580
that makes things look really weird in any one partition

00:56:45.580 --> 00:56:46.620
of the data that you're looking at.

00:56:47.659 --> 00:56:51.179
Hopefully that helps because I could go on for like an hour and a half.

00:56:51.179 --> 00:56:51.739
Thank you.

00:56:51.739 --> 00:56:52.699
No, thank you very much.

00:56:52.699 --> 00:56:55.020
We threw a lot at you with that one question.

00:56:55.820 --> 00:56:58.459
I think we have time for one more question.

00:56:58.459 --> 00:57:02.699
Kalau, I see you had asked something a bit earlier about training.

00:57:02.699 --> 00:57:04.139
Do you want to jump in with your question?

00:57:06.540 --> 00:57:07.340
Yeah, sure.

00:57:07.340 --> 00:57:08.459
I'm happy to jump in.

00:57:08.459 --> 00:57:09.100
Hi, Matt.

00:57:09.100 --> 00:57:10.060
My name is Kalau.

00:57:10.060 --> 00:57:12.780
I'm a customer success rep here at Posit.

00:57:14.139 --> 00:57:16.780
She's actually my customer success rep.

00:57:16.780 --> 00:57:20.620
Yes, for Pi Insurance and a few others on the call actually.

00:57:20.620 --> 00:57:24.620
But yeah, there seems to be so much to know in this space,

00:57:24.620 --> 00:57:27.580
not just for insurance, but like data science, programming in general.

00:57:29.020 --> 00:57:32.139
And as somebody who might be just starting out in industry

00:57:32.139 --> 00:57:36.939
or coming out of college, how would they get a job?

00:57:36.939 --> 00:57:41.419
I guess, what skills or knowledge do you think they should have

00:57:41.419 --> 00:57:45.739
or what are teams like yours looking for in new hires?

00:57:46.459 --> 00:57:47.580
It's a really good question.

00:57:48.300 --> 00:57:51.899
I mean, so I think a working knowledge of both Python,

00:57:51.899 --> 00:57:54.379
and I'm going to say it, R, right?

00:57:54.379 --> 00:57:55.419
R and Python.

00:57:55.419 --> 00:57:57.739
A working knowledge of both of those is really important.

00:57:58.860 --> 00:58:03.340
The biggest piece of the puzzle for me is an understanding of

00:58:04.540 --> 00:58:09.500
what I would call pragmatic, productionalizable model building, right?

00:58:10.620 --> 00:58:17.100
Do not narrow your scope or your interest down to research alone.

00:58:17.100 --> 00:58:19.820
You need to know how to get models into production

00:58:19.820 --> 00:58:23.820
so that they can be used by actors in the real world, right?

00:58:23.820 --> 00:58:27.739
If you're doing descriptive statistics, that's great.

00:58:27.739 --> 00:58:29.739
I mean, and if that's what you want to do, great.

00:58:29.739 --> 00:58:32.379
But you're going to cut yourself short

00:58:32.379 --> 00:58:33.979
if you don't know how to deploy a model.

00:58:33.979 --> 00:58:36.060
You're going to cut yourself short if you don't know

00:58:36.060 --> 00:58:39.100
what the process looks like in order to deploy a model.

00:58:39.100 --> 00:58:41.739
You don't necessarily need to know how to do the engineering, right?

00:58:41.739 --> 00:58:43.340
You can get an MLOps team for that.

00:58:43.340 --> 00:58:45.100
But you need to know as a data scientist,

00:58:45.100 --> 00:58:47.260
how to do things like parity testing,

00:58:47.899 --> 00:58:49.899
predictions between the production environment

00:58:49.899 --> 00:58:51.580
and the model build environment, right?

00:58:51.580 --> 00:58:53.020
You need to understand what that looks like,

00:58:53.020 --> 00:58:54.699
what the process looks like, right?

00:58:54.699 --> 00:58:57.020
And you need to understand how to actually go

00:58:57.020 --> 00:58:59.500
the last mile, if you will, right?

00:58:59.500 --> 00:59:01.419
If you're just building general linear models

00:59:01.419 --> 00:59:02.699
and you're doing that descriptively and you're saying,

00:59:02.699 --> 00:59:04.540
look, I built a model and it looks great, right?

00:59:04.540 --> 00:59:07.899
The next question that any executive is going to ask you is,

00:59:07.899 --> 00:59:09.179
okay, how do we use this?

00:59:09.179 --> 00:59:10.459
How are we going to deploy this?

00:59:10.459 --> 00:59:11.820
Are we going to deploy it in SQL?

00:59:11.820 --> 00:59:12.939
Are we going to containerize it?

00:59:12.939 --> 00:59:14.219
Are we going to use Scala?

00:59:14.219 --> 00:59:15.659
Are we going to do something else

00:59:15.659 --> 00:59:18.219
in order to get that model into PMML,

00:59:18.219 --> 00:59:19.419
whatever the case may be?

00:59:19.419 --> 00:59:21.500
How do we get that model into production?

00:59:21.500 --> 00:59:23.260
And how do we know that that production model

00:59:23.260 --> 00:59:25.419
is going to score the same way

00:59:25.419 --> 00:59:27.100
as it did in the model build environment?

00:59:27.100 --> 00:59:30.060
I think the other one is having a really good understanding

00:59:30.060 --> 00:59:32.459
and an ability to articulate

00:59:32.459 --> 00:59:34.379
what the model building process looks like

00:59:34.379 --> 00:59:37.739
all the way from finding the data sources

00:59:37.739 --> 00:59:40.219
all the way through to validating that model

00:59:40.219 --> 00:59:43.419
and making sure that you don't have an overflip model

00:59:43.500 --> 00:59:45.820
and that that model is really going to perform

00:59:45.820 --> 00:59:48.780
as you say it's going to perform in the real world

00:59:48.780 --> 00:59:50.379
on data that it hasn't seen before.

00:59:50.379 --> 00:59:51.659
Those are all really, really important.

00:59:51.659 --> 00:59:53.179
The last point that I'll make is,

00:59:53.179 --> 00:59:55.260
it is critically important for you to show

00:59:55.899 --> 01:00:00.379
in any interview or to any business manager

01:00:00.379 --> 01:00:03.179
that you have a high level of curiosity

01:00:03.179 --> 01:00:05.020
in the business that you're in.

01:00:05.659 --> 01:00:09.260
Don't sell yourself short and just be a data scientist.

01:00:09.820 --> 01:00:12.219
You need to be a curious data scientist.

01:00:12.219 --> 01:00:15.260
If it's an insurance, you need to want to learn insurance.

01:00:15.260 --> 01:00:18.939
If it's in aeronautics, you need to want to learn aeronautics.

01:00:18.939 --> 01:00:22.139
If it's in process optimization for, I don't know,

01:00:22.139 --> 01:00:24.620
making candy bars, you need to really be curious

01:00:24.620 --> 01:00:26.780
and interested in what the process looks like

01:00:26.780 --> 01:00:28.860
to make a candy bar, right?

01:00:28.860 --> 01:00:30.860
I think that that's really, really important

01:00:30.860 --> 01:00:33.500
is that data scientists can't just be data scientists.

01:00:33.500 --> 01:00:35.580
They have to be Renaissance people

01:00:37.179 --> 01:00:39.659
and constantly curious and autodidactic.

01:00:40.379 --> 01:00:43.739
That's the best advice that I can give

01:00:44.620 --> 01:00:46.379
is don't narrow yourself.

01:00:46.379 --> 01:00:50.300
Don't be an inch wide and a mile deep.

01:00:51.340 --> 01:00:54.620
Be a mile wide and more than a few inches deep.

01:00:55.580 --> 01:00:57.340
Great, thanks, Matt.

01:00:58.860 --> 01:00:59.899
Thank you so much, Matt.

01:00:59.899 --> 01:01:02.620
I know we quickly came to the top of the hour here,

01:01:02.620 --> 01:01:05.500
but I really appreciated this conversation

01:01:05.500 --> 01:01:07.580
and you jumping on here and joining us.

01:01:08.219 --> 01:01:09.179
Absolutely my pleasure.

01:01:09.179 --> 01:01:09.899
I had a fun time.

01:01:10.620 --> 01:01:12.699
Thank you all for all the great questions too.

01:01:12.699 --> 01:01:16.459
I'm going to put Matt's LinkedIn in the chat here

01:01:16.459 --> 01:01:18.860
if anybody wants to connect,

01:01:18.860 --> 01:01:21.179
but also I will share the recording, of course,

01:01:21.179 --> 01:01:24.699
to YouTube and to the Posit Data Science Hangout site.

01:01:24.699 --> 01:01:26.540
Have a great rest of the day, everybody.

